caption: The pass-through field picker
tags: $:/plugins/crosseye/json-convert/usage/editor
title: $:/plugins/crosseye/json-convert/usage/editor/pass-through
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

Beside the Custom Fields header sits a ''Pick fields…'' button.  It opens a modal showing every leaf field in the source JSON's record-scoped shape, each with a checkbox and a proposed field name.  Tick the fields you want; click ''Apply''.  Each ticked leaf becomes a custom-fields entry of the form `"<name>": "{{<path>}}"` — pure pass-through, no transform.

The picker is the right tool when most of the source's fields should land verbatim in the produced tiddlers and only a handful of "cruft" or sensitive fields need to be skipped.  Click ''Pick fields…'', tick the ''All'' checkbox at the top to select every leaf, untick the fields you don't want, ''Apply''.  Try it on the demo wiki's [[Example Moodle Gradebook]] — paste [[Example Moodle Gradebook Data]] as the source, open the editor, click the ''All'' checkbox, then untick `internal_id`, `system_token`, `audit_trail`, and `picture`.

''The All checkbox.''  Above the leaf list, an ''All'' checkbox is tri-state: //unchecked// when nothing's ticked, //checked// when every leaf is ticked, //indeterminate// when some are.  Clicking it toggles between full and empty selection.  Customized bindings are untouched — All only affects pure pass-throughs.

''How recognition works.''  When the picker opens, it walks your existing custom-fields and pre-ticks every binding whose value is exactly `{{<path>}}` and whose name is a plausible flattening of `<path>` (last segment, slugified; or the last two segments joined; or the full path joined).  Bindings with transforms or extra text are //customized//, not pass-throughs — they don't appear in the picker, and unticking does not affect them.

''Field-name flattening.''  A path's proposed field name is its last segment, slugified.  If that's already taken — by an existing binding or another tick — the picker walks back one segment and joins with `-`.  So `author.name` becomes `name`, but if `name` is taken, `author-name`.  Names are editable inline before Apply.

''What the picker does not cover.''  Leaves whose path traverses an array (e.g. `enrolledcourses[*].name`) aren't tickable — the engine rejects `[*]` inside binding tokens.  Use the regular Browse modal to bind to a specific element (`enrolledcourses[0].name`).  And the picker only adds rows to `custom-fields`; tw-fields (title, tags, …) are left alone, even when a tw-fields binding is itself a pass-through.
